ateId\":\"wall-slides\",\"sets\":\"3×10\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"shoulder-sleeper-stretch\",\"sets\":\"2 min each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"hollow-body-hold\",\"sets\":\"3×20-30 sec\"}]},{\"id\":\"knee-hip-mobility\",\"title\":\"Session B: Knee & Hip Mobility\",\"subtitle\":\"15-20 min — Do 2x per week\",\"description\":\"Your lateral lunge pain and cross-legged sitting difficulty both point to tight hip adductors and weak VMO (inner quad). This session opens the hips and builds the knee stability that lets you load lateral movements safely. The Cossack squat is your eventual goal movement.\",\"folderGroup\":\"Phase 1: Joint Restoration\",\"sortOrder\":3,\"color\":\"rgb(96, 200, 140)\",\"exercises\":[{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"ninety-ninety-hip-switches\",\"sets\":\"3×8 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"glute-bridge\",\"sets\":\"3×12\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"banded-clamshells\",\"sets\":\"3×15 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"tibialis-raises\",\"sets\":\"3×15\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"banded-tke\",\"sets\":\"3×15 each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"atg-split-squat\",\"sets\":\"3×8 each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"cossack-squat\",\"sets\":\"3×6 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"active-frog-stretch\",\"sets\":\"2×45 sec\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"copenhagen-plank\",\"sets\":\"3×15-20 sec each side\"}]},{\"id\":\"ankle-integration\",\"title\":\"Session C: Ankle/Achilles & Integration\",\"subtitle\":\"15-20 min — Do 1-2x per week\",\"description\":\"Your repaired Achilles needs consistent eccentric loading to stay resilient — this is backed by decades of research (Alfredson protocol). Combined with dorsiflexion work, this session protects the ankle and unlocks deeper squat positions. The balance work re-trains proprioception that was disrupted by the surgery.\",\"folderGroup\":\"Phase 1: Joint Restoration\",\"sortOrder\":4,\"color\":\"rgb(180, 140, 224)\",\"exercises\":[{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"extended-ankle-cars\",\"sets\":\"2×8 each direction, each foot\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"eccentric-calf-raises\",\"sets\":\"3×15 each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"wall-dorsiflexion\",\"sets\":\"3×30 sec each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"single-leg-balance\",\"sets\":\"3×30 sec each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"supported-deep-squat\",\"sets\":\"3×30-45 sec\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"dead-bugs\",\"sets\":\"3×8 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"bear-crawl\",\"sets\":\"2×30 sec\"}]},{\"id\":\"core-stability\",\"title\":\"Session D: Core Stability\",\"subtitle\":\"15-20 min — Do 1-2x per week\",\"description\":\"Your shoulders, knees, and ankles all depend on a stable trunk. When the core can't hold position, your joints compensate — that's a big part of why you keep getting injured. This session trains anti-extension, anti-rotation, and anti-lateral-flexion — the three pillars of functional core stability. These aren't crunches; they teach your core to resist unwanted movement so your limbs can move freely. Exercises marked with ◆ in other sessions are drawn from here.\",\"folderGroup\":\"Phase 1: Joint Restoration\",\"sortOrder\":5,\"color\":\"rgb(224, 120, 150)\",\"exercises\":[{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"dead-bugs\",\"sets\":\"3×10 each side\",\"notes\":\"The king of core exercises for your situation. Lie on back, arms up, knees at 90°. Press lower back into floor — this is the cue that matters. Extend opposite arm and leg while maintaining ZERO low back movement. Slow and controlled — 3 seconds out, 3 seconds back. If your back arches, shorten the range. Progress by holding a light dumbbell overhead or adding a band around your feet.\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"pallof-press\",\"sets\":\"3×10 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"bird-dogs\",\"sets\":\"3×8 each side\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"hollow-body-hold\",\"sets\":\"3×30 sec\",\"notes\":\"Arms overhead, legs extended, low back pressed into floor, shoulders and feet lifted. Scale it: bent knees with arms at sides (easiest) → straight legs with arms at sides → straight legs with arms overhead (hardest). If you can hold 30s at the hardest version, you can progress to hollow body rocks.\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"copenhagen-plank\",\"sets\":\"3×20-30 sec each side\",\"notes\":\"Side plank with top leg on bench, bottom leg free. Trains lateral core and adductors simultaneously. Regression: bend bottom knee to floor, or use a shorter bench so you're supporting from the knee instead of the foot. Progression: add hip dips (lower and lift hips while holding). This exercise alone can fix a lot of your lateral movement issues.\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"suitcase-carry\",\"sets\":\"3×30 sec each side\"}]},{\"id\":\"active-recovery\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery\",\"subtitle\":\"20-30 min — Do 1-2x per week\",\"folderGroup\":\"Recovery\",\"description\":\"Easy effort only. The purpose is blood flow, not fitness. If you find yourself breathing hard on the bike, you're going too hard. Pair with foam rolling to address tissue quality.\",\"sortOrder\":6,\"color\":\"rgb(200, 196, 120)\",\"exercises\":[{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"stationary-bike\",\"sets\":\"15-20 min\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"foam-roll-quads\",\"sets\":\"2 min each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"foam-roll-calves\",\"sets\":\"2 min each leg\"},{\"exerciseTemplateId\":\"lacrosse-ball-shoulder\",\"sets\":\"2 min each side\"}]}]"
